<font color="#FF0000">OF SHOES&amp;SHIPS&amp;REMFS&amp;FNGS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Apr 20 14:18:06 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Spatz,<br>
     Hope Arthur explained the terms well.  Actually it was possible to be both in Vietnam.  When I reported to the 172nd Military Intelligence Co. (the good ol' contradiction in terms) as a green leg (&quot;non-jump qualified) 2nd LT in an airborne unit; I became both a REMF and the ultimate FNG.<br>
     Seriously though, am grateful I only spent one night on an outpost beyond a battalion perimemter where I spent the night staring down the muzzle of my M-16 wandering whether I would have to pull the trigger. That and the most vicious cold weather mosquitos (it can get down to 40 in the mountains in January at night)kept me wide awake at my position. Although I outranked him and was technically &quot;combat arms&quot;; I had sense enough to defer to the experience and wisdom the staff sergeant squad leader. Contrary to popular opinion, some of us officers knew who buttered our bread, namely the guys with the stripes; and it wasn't just a matter of being saved from our own ignorance or stupidity for pride's sake, but it meant giving everyone a better chance of going back home in one piece alive.<br><br>
PS.  Did not fall thru a black hole the past month. Just have not been able to get online lately. Realize the importance of trying to keep this site alive. 
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


